    \begin {tikzcd}
      \ker (f)\ar [r, shift left=.2em]\ar [r, shift right=.2em] &
      x\ar [r, "f"]\ar [d, two heads] & y\makebox [0pt][l]{,} \\
      & x/\ker (f)\ar [ur, hookrightarrow]
    \end {tikzcd}


 where the map x/\ker (f)\hookrightarrow  y is induced by the universal property of
  the quotient. Uniqueness of this factorization comes from the
  fact that regular epimorphisms are strong, so that regular epis are
  the orthgonal class to monos. It now remains to show that the map
  x/\ker (f)\xhookrightarrow {i} y is actually a monomorphism. Call this map i; the
  idea is to show that the legs of the kernel pair of i agree.

Let \ker (i)\rightrightarrows  x/\ker (f) be the kernel pair of i. By
  commutativity of the above diagram, the universal property of the
  pullback induces a map \ker (f)\xrightarrow {q} \ker (i): 




    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
